1
00:00:06,590 --> 00:00:08,050
(SCREAMING)

2
00:00:16,475 --> 00:00:20,103
We are under attack. There are creatures.

3
00:00:20,229 --> 00:00:22,523
I don't even think they're human.
We can't stop them.

4
00:00:22,606 --> 00:00:25,692
The clock is broken. He's coming.

5
00:00:25,776 --> 00:00:27,903
Did you hear what I said?

6
00:00:29,279 --> 00:00:32,783
Listen to me.
There is a man coming to Versailles.

7
00:00:32,866 --> 00:00:36,286
He has watched over me my whole life
and he will not desert me tonight.

8
00:00:36,411 --> 00:00:38,497
What are you talking about? What man?

9
00:00:38,580 --> 00:00:41,500
The only man, save you, I have ever loved.

10
00:00:41,625 --> 00:00:45,212
No, don't look like that. There's no time.
You have your duties.

11
00:00:45,295 --> 00:00:48,006
I am your mistress. Go to your queen.

12
00:00:49,967 --> 00:00:52,636
Are you there? Can you hear me?

13
00:00:54,054 --> 00:00:58,433
I need you now, you promised.
The clock on the mantel is broken.

14
00:00:58,517 --> 00:01:00,060
It is time.

15
00:01:00,143 --> 00:01:02,396
Doctor! Doctor!

16
00:01:03,981 --> 00:01:05,649
(DOCTOR WHO THEME)

17
00:01:44,855 --> 00:01:47,065
(WHOOSHING)

18
00:01:55,157 --> 00:01:59,911
It's a spaceship. Brilliant!
I got a spaceship on my first go.

19
00:01:59,995 --> 00:02:02,289
ROSE: Looks kind of abandoned.
Anyone on board?

20
00:02:02,372 --> 00:02:05,042
Nah, nothing here.
Well, nothing dangerous.

21
00:02:05,167 --> 00:02:07,294
Well, not that dangerous.

22
00:02:08,587 --> 00:02:10,797
You know what? I'll just have a quick scan.

23
00:02:10,881 --> 00:02:13,759
In case there's anything dangerous.

24
00:02:13,842 --> 00:02:17,012
So, what's the date? How far have we gone?

25
00:02:17,095 --> 00:02:19,848
About 3,000 years into your future,
give or take.

26
00:02:19,931 --> 00:02:21,642
(ELECTRONIC HUMMING)

27
00:02:21,725 --> 00:02:23,644
DOCTOR: 51st century.

28
00:02:24,478 --> 00:02:27,606
The Dagmar Cluster,
you're a long way from home, Mickey!

29
00:02:27,689 --> 00:02:29,191
Two and a half galaxies.

30
00:02:29,274 --> 00:02:31,860
Mickey Smith, meet the universe.

31
00:02:32,903 --> 00:02:35,113
See anything you like?

32
00:02:35,197 --> 00:02:36,907
It's so realistic!

33
00:02:37,074 --> 00:02:41,912
Dear me, had some cowboys in here.
Been a ton of repair work going on.

34
00:02:44,206 --> 00:02:48,960
Now that's odd, look at that.
All the warp engines are going.

35
00:02:50,504 --> 00:02:52,089
Full capacity.

36
00:02:53,048 --> 00:02:56,760
There's enough power running through
this ship to punch a hole in the universe

37
00:02:56,885 --> 00:02:59,137
and we're not moving.

38
00:02:59,262 --> 00:03:00,764
So where's all that power going?

39
00:03:00,847 --> 00:03:02,766
Where'd all the crew go?

40
00:03:02,849 --> 00:03:04,851
Good question. No life readings on board.

41
00:03:04,935 --> 00:03:08,355
Well, we're in deep space.
They didn't just nip out for a quick fag.

42
00:03:08,438 --> 00:03:10,607
No, I've checked all the smoking pods.

43
00:03:12,526 --> 00:03:14,820
-You smell that?
-Yeah. Someone's cooking.

44
00:03:14,903 --> 00:03:16,363
Sunday roast, definitely.

45
00:03:22,536 --> 00:03:26,623
Now, there's something you don't see
in your average spaceship.

46
00:03:27,666 --> 00:03:30,377
18th century. French.

47
00:03:30,877 --> 00:03:32,254
Nice mantel.

48
00:03:33,714 --> 00:03:35,340
Not a hologram.

49
00:03:36,633 --> 00:03:41,221
Not even a reproduction. This actually is
an 18th-century French fireplace.

50
00:03:41,304 --> 00:03:43,390
Double-sided.
There's another room through there.

51
00:03:43,473 --> 00:03:45,767
It can't be. That's the outer hull
of the ship. Look.

52
00:03:45,851 --> 00:03:47,936
-Hello.
-Hello?

53
00:03:48,019 --> 00:03:50,480
-What's your name?
-Reinette.

54
00:03:50,564 --> 00:03:52,858
Reinette. That's a lovely name.

55
00:03:52,983 --> 00:03:55,652
Can you tell me where you are
at the moment, Reinette?

56
00:03:55,736 --> 00:03:57,320
In my bedroom.

57
00:03:57,738 --> 00:04:00,115
And where's your bedroom?
Where do you live, Reinette?

58
00:04:00,198 --> 00:04:02,701
-Paris of course.
-Paris. Right.

59
00:04:03,410 --> 00:04:06,413
Monsieur, what are you doing
in my fireplace?

60
00:04:06,496 --> 00:04:10,417
Oh, it's just a routine...fire check.

61
00:04:10,500 --> 00:04:12,002
Can you tell me what year it is?

62
00:04:12,085 --> 00:04:15,338
Of course I can. 1727.

63
00:04:15,464 --> 00:04:18,091
Right, lovely, one of my favourites.

64
00:04:18,592 --> 00:04:21,136
August is rubbish, though. Stay indoors.

65
00:04:21,219 --> 00:04:24,097
Okay, that's all for now.
Thanks for your help.

66
00:04:24,181 --> 00:04:26,516
Hope you enjoy the rest of the fire.
Night-night.

67
00:04:26,600 --> 00:04:28,351
Good night, monsieur.

68
00:04:28,477 --> 00:04:30,103
You said this was the 51st century.

69
00:04:30,187 --> 00:04:33,398
I also said this ship was generating enough
power to punch a hole in the universe.

70
00:04:33,523 --> 00:04:35,567
I think we just found the hole.

71
00:04:35,650 --> 00:04:38,403
-Must be a spatio-temporal hyperlink.
-What's that?

72
00:04:38,528 --> 00:04:42,365
No idea, just made it up.
Didn't want to say "magic door".

73
00:04:42,491 --> 00:04:47,204
And on the other side of the "magic door"
it's France in 17277

74
00:04:47,329 --> 00:04:50,665
Well, she was speaking French.
Right period French, too.

75
00:04:50,749 --> 00:04:52,417
She was speaking English, I heard her.

76
00:04:52,501 --> 00:04:54,294
That's the Tardis, translates for you.

77
00:04:54,377 --> 00:04:56,171
-Even French?
-Yep.

78
00:04:57,047 --> 00:04:58,924
-Got you.
-ROSE: Doctor!

79
00:05:18,026 --> 00:05:19,986
(HORSES TROTTING)

80
00:05:23,949 --> 00:05:25,408
(GASPS)

81
00:05:25,534 --> 00:05:29,621
It's okay. Don't scream.
It's me. It's the fireplace man, look.

82
00:05:33,542 --> 00:05:36,002
We were talking. Just a moment ago.
I was in your fireplace.

83
00:05:36,086 --> 00:05:39,673
Monsieur, that was weeks ago.
That was months.

84
00:05:39,798 --> 00:05:42,175
Really? Hmm.

85
00:05:45,595 --> 00:05:49,432
Must be a loose connection.
Need to get a man in.

86
00:05:49,516 --> 00:05:52,310
Who are you and what are you doing here?

87
00:05:52,435 --> 00:05:53,770
(TICKING)

88
00:05:55,605 --> 00:05:58,900
-Okay. That's scary.
-You're scared of a broken clock?

89
00:05:58,984 --> 00:06:01,278
Just a bit scared, yeah. Just a little tiny bit.

90
00:06:01,403 --> 00:06:04,447
'Cause, you see, if this clock's broken,

91
00:06:04,573 --> 00:06:07,117
and it's the only clock in the room,

92
00:06:09,619 --> 00:06:11,496
then what's that?

93
00:06:11,621 --> 00:06:13,206
(TICKING)

94
00:06:14,541 --> 00:06:17,419
'Cause, you see, that's not a clock.

95
00:06:17,502 --> 00:06:20,422
You can tell by the resonance. Too big.

96
00:06:22,841 --> 00:06:27,137
Six feet, I'd say. Size of a man.

97
00:06:27,846 --> 00:06:29,764
What is it?

98
00:06:29,848 --> 00:06:31,558
Now let's think.

99
00:06:31,641 --> 00:06:34,269
If you were a thing that ticked
and you were hiding in someone's bedroom,

100
00:06:34,394 --> 00:06:35,896
first thing you do, break the clock.

101
00:06:36,021 --> 00:06:39,190
No one notices the sound
of one clock ticking, but two?

102
00:06:41,359 --> 00:06:44,529
You might start to wonder
if you're really alone.

103
00:06:47,657 --> 00:06:49,910
Stay on the bed. Right in the middle.

104
00:06:49,993 --> 00:06:53,038
Don't put your hands or feet over the edge.

105
00:07:18,021 --> 00:07:21,149
Reinette, don't look round.

106
00:07:22,859 --> 00:07:25,278
You stay exactly where you are.

107
00:07:31,701 --> 00:07:33,745
Hold still, let me look.

108
00:07:35,872 --> 00:07:38,291
You've been scanning her brain!

109
00:07:39,417 --> 00:07:41,294
You've crossed two galaxies
and thousands of years

110
00:07:41,378 --> 00:07:43,004
just to scan a child's brain?

111
00:07:43,088 --> 00:07:46,716
What could there be in a little girl's mind
worth blowing a hole in the universe?

112
00:07:46,800 --> 00:07:48,635
I don't understand.

113
00:07:48,718 --> 00:07:50,220
It wants me?

114
00:07:51,137 --> 00:07:52,639
You want me?

115
00:07:53,348 --> 00:07:55,684
Not yet. You are incomplete.

116
00:07:55,767 --> 00:07:58,770
Incomplete?
What does that mean, incomplete?

117
00:07:58,853 --> 00:08:02,565
You can answer her, you can answer me.
What do you mean, incomplete?

118
00:08:07,445 --> 00:08:09,197
Monsieur, be careful!

119
00:08:09,280 --> 00:08:11,366
It's just a nightmare, Reinette.
Don't worry about it.

120
00:08:11,449 --> 00:08:13,493
Everyone has nightmares.

121
00:08:13,576 --> 00:08:17,080
Even monsters from under the bed
have nightmares. Don't you, Monster?

122
00:08:17,163 --> 00:08:19,499
What do monsters have nightmares about?

123
00:08:19,582 --> 00:08:20,875
Me. Ha!

124
00:08:23,586 --> 00:08:24,921
Doctor!

125
00:08:37,434 --> 00:08:39,144
Excellent. Ice gun.

126
00:08:39,269 --> 00:08:40,562
Fire extinguisher.

127
00:08:40,687 --> 00:08:42,647
-Where did that thing come from?
-Here.

128
00:08:42,772 --> 00:08:44,149
MICKEY: So why is it dressed like that?

129
00:08:44,274 --> 00:08:47,110
Field trip to France.
Some kind of basic camouflage protocol.

130
00:08:47,235 --> 00:08:49,988
Nice needlework. Shame about the face.

131
00:08:51,281 --> 00:08:54,743
Oh, you are beautiful!

132
00:08:56,119 --> 00:08:59,622
No, really, you are. You're gorgeous.
Look at that!

133
00:08:59,789 --> 00:09:02,500
Space age clockwork. I love it.
I've got chills!

134
00:09:02,584 --> 00:09:04,085
Listen, seriously,

135
00:09:04,169 --> 00:09:06,546
I mean this from the heart,
and by the way, count those,

136
00:09:06,629 --> 00:09:10,717
it would be a crime,
it would be an act of vandalism,

137
00:09:10,800 --> 00:09:12,635
to disassemble you.

138
00:09:13,428 --> 00:09:14,971
But that won't stop me.

139
00:09:15,096 --> 00:09:16,473
(CREAKING)

140
00:09:20,769 --> 00:09:23,188
Short-range teleport.
Can't have got far. Could still be on board.

141
00:09:23,313 --> 00:09:25,732
-What is it?
-Don't go looking for it.

142
00:09:25,815 --> 00:09:28,234
-Where are you going?
-Back in a sec.

143
00:09:34,699 --> 00:09:37,660
-He said not to look for it.
-Yeah, he did.

144
00:09:43,416 --> 00:09:45,460
Now you're getting it.

145
00:09:50,006 --> 00:09:51,341
Reinette?

146
00:09:52,467 --> 00:09:54,385
Just checking you're okay.

147
00:09:57,013 --> 00:09:58,973
(PLAYING HARP)

148
00:10:03,061 --> 00:10:04,854
(CLEARING THROAT)

149
00:10:06,231 --> 00:10:08,108
Oh. Hello!

150
00:10:10,527 --> 00:10:14,739
I was just looking for Reinette.
This is still her room, isn't it?

151
00:10:15,448 --> 00:10:18,034
I've been away, not sure how long.

152
00:10:18,118 --> 00:10:20,495
WOMAN: Reinette? We're ready to go!

153
00:10:20,578 --> 00:10:23,915
Go to the carriage, Mother,
I will join you there.

154
00:10:27,127 --> 00:10:29,796
It is customary, I think,
to have an imaginary friend

155
00:10:29,879 --> 00:10:32,215
only during one's childhood.

156
00:10:32,382 --> 00:10:35,051
You are to be congratulated
on your persistence.

157
00:10:35,135 --> 00:10:36,511
Reinette.

158
00:10:38,388 --> 00:10:40,306
Well...

159
00:10:40,390 --> 00:10:41,975
Goodness, how you've grown.

160
00:10:42,058 --> 00:10:45,353
And you do not appear
to have aged a single day.

161
00:10:45,854 --> 00:10:48,148
That is tremendously impolite of you.

162
00:10:48,231 --> 00:10:50,567
Right, yes, sorry. Um...

163
00:10:52,777 --> 00:10:56,614
Listen, lovely to catch up
but better be off, eh?

164
00:10:56,739 --> 00:10:59,868
Don't want your mother finding you
up here with a strange man, do we?

165
00:10:59,951 --> 00:11:02,495
Strange?
How could you be a stranger to me?

166
00:11:02,579 --> 00:11:04,914
I have known you
since I was seven years old.

167
00:11:05,081 --> 00:11:09,043
Yeah, I suppose you have.
I came the quick route.

168
00:11:13,923 --> 00:11:17,010
You seem to be flesh and blood at any rate,
but this is absurd.

169
00:11:17,093 --> 00:11:19,637
Reason tells me you cannot be real.

170
00:11:19,762 --> 00:11:22,765
Oh, you never want to listen to reason.

171
00:11:23,933 --> 00:11:26,895
MAN: Mademoiselle?
Your mother grows impatient.

172
00:11:26,978 --> 00:11:28,396
A moment!

173
00:11:29,856 --> 00:11:32,775
So many questions. So little time.

174
00:11:42,785 --> 00:11:43,870
(DOOR SLAMMING)

175
00:11:43,953 --> 00:11:46,080
MAN: Mademoiselle Poisson!

176
00:11:57,550 --> 00:11:58,885
Poisson?

177
00:12:00,803 --> 00:12:03,181
Reinette Poisson. No!

178
00:12:03,890 --> 00:12:06,726
No, no, no, no! No way! Reinette Poisson.

179
00:12:06,809 --> 00:12:09,103
Later Madame d'Etioles.
Later still, mistress of Louis XV,

180
00:12:09,187 --> 00:12:10,939
uncrowned Queen of France!

181
00:12:11,022 --> 00:12:14,651
Actress, artist, musician, dancer, courtesan.

182
00:12:14,734 --> 00:12:16,527
Fantastic gardener.

183
00:12:18,404 --> 00:12:20,782
Who the hell are you?

184
00:12:20,865 --> 00:12:25,036
I'm the Doctor.
And I just snogged Madame de Pompadour.

185
00:12:25,119 --> 00:12:26,871
(LAUGHS GLEEFULLY)

186
00:12:29,624 --> 00:12:30,792
Rose!

187
00:12:32,710 --> 00:12:36,547
Mickey! Every time. Every time!
It's rule one. Don't wander off.

188
00:12:36,631 --> 00:12:38,800
I tell them, I do. Rule one.

189
00:12:38,883 --> 00:12:41,636
There could be anything on this ship!

190
00:12:44,806 --> 00:12:46,266
(NEIGHING)

191
00:13:01,030 --> 00:13:03,032
Are you looking at me?

192
00:13:03,533 --> 00:13:04,742
(EXCLAIMS)

193
00:13:06,077 --> 00:13:07,870
Look! Look at this!

194
00:13:11,040 --> 00:13:14,043
That's an eye in there. That's a real eye.

195
00:13:19,465 --> 00:13:21,551
(RHYTHMIC BEATING)

196
00:13:31,728 --> 00:13:33,521
What is that?

197
00:13:33,604 --> 00:13:37,317
What's that in the middle there?
Looks like it's wired in.

198
00:13:37,400 --> 00:13:39,319
It's a heart, Mickey.

199
00:13:40,987 --> 00:13:42,864
It's a human heart.

200
00:13:45,658 --> 00:13:46,909
Rose?

201
00:13:53,583 --> 00:13:56,919
Will you stop following me?
I'm not your mother.

202
00:14:01,424 --> 00:14:04,260
So this is where you came from,
eh, horsey?

203
00:14:07,847 --> 00:14:09,682
(WOMEN GIGGLING)

204
00:14:10,683 --> 00:14:13,311
Oh, Katherine, you are too wicked.

205
00:14:15,063 --> 00:14:16,481
Oh, speaking of wicked,

206
00:14:16,564 --> 00:14:20,068
I hear Madame de Chateauroux is ill
and close to death.

207
00:14:20,151 --> 00:14:23,821
-Yes, I am devastated.
-Oh, indeed.

208
00:14:23,905 --> 00:14:26,741
I, myself, am frequently inconsolable.

209
00:14:28,284 --> 00:14:31,245
KATHERINE: The King will therefore
be requiring a new mistress.

210
00:14:31,329 --> 00:14:32,830
You love the King, of course.

211
00:14:32,914 --> 00:14:36,167
He is the King
and I love him with all my heart.

212
00:14:36,709 --> 00:14:39,212
And I look forward to meeting him.

213
00:14:39,295 --> 00:14:41,547
(BIRD CALLING IN DISTANCE)

214
00:14:42,924 --> 00:14:45,218
Is something wrong, my dear?

215
00:14:45,802 --> 00:14:47,345
Not wrong, no.

216
00:14:49,305 --> 00:14:51,724
KATHERINE: Every woman in Paris
knows your ambitions.

217
00:14:51,808 --> 00:14:53,810
REINETTE: Every woman in Paris
shares them.

218
00:14:53,893 --> 00:14:56,437
You know, of course, that the King
is to attend the Yew Tree Ball...

219
00:15:03,319 --> 00:15:06,656
-Maybe it wasn't a real heart.
-Of course it was a real heart.

220
00:15:06,823 --> 00:15:08,658
(CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKING)

221
00:15:08,741 --> 00:15:11,702
Is this, like, normal for you?
Is this an average day?

222
00:15:11,828 --> 00:15:15,081
Life with the Doctor, Mickey,
no more average days.

223
00:15:15,206 --> 00:15:17,959
It's France again. We can see France.

224
00:15:19,168 --> 00:15:22,004
I think we're looking through a mirror.

225
00:15:23,548 --> 00:15:25,216
Blimey, look at this guy!

226
00:15:25,299 --> 00:15:27,552
-Who does he think he is?
-King of France.

227
00:15:27,635 --> 00:15:30,930
-Oh, here's trouble. What you been up to?
-Oh, this and that.

228
00:15:31,013 --> 00:15:33,266
Became the imaginary friend
of a future French aristocrat,

229
00:15:33,349 --> 00:15:34,934
picked a fight with a clockwork man.

230
00:15:35,017 --> 00:15:36,394
(HORSE WHINNYING)

231
00:15:36,477 --> 00:15:38,104
Oh, and I met a horse.

232
00:15:38,187 --> 00:15:40,523
What's a horse doing on a spaceship?

233
00:15:40,606 --> 00:15:42,775
Mickey, what's pre-revolutionary France
doing on a spaceship?

234
00:15:42,859 --> 00:15:44,402
Get a little perspective.

235
00:15:44,485 --> 00:15:47,989
See these?
They're all over the place, on every deck.

236
00:15:48,156 --> 00:15:50,074
Gateways to history.

237
00:15:50,616 --> 00:15:54,036
But not just any old history. Hers.

238
00:15:54,704 --> 00:15:56,622
Time window.

239
00:15:56,706 --> 00:15:59,834
Deliberately arranged
along the life of one particular woman.

240
00:15:59,917 --> 00:16:04,714
A spaceship from the 51st century
stalking a woman from the 18th.

241
00:16:05,006 --> 00:16:07,175
-Why?
-Who is she?

242
00:16:07,258 --> 00:16:09,927
Jean-Antoinette Poisson.
Known to her friends as Reinette.

243
00:16:10,011 --> 00:16:11,929
One of the most accomplished women
who ever lived.

244
00:16:12,054 --> 00:16:13,973
So has she got plans
for being the queen, then?

245
00:16:14,056 --> 00:16:17,894
No, he's already got a queen.
She's got plans on being his mistress.

246
00:16:17,977 --> 00:16:21,314
Oh, I get it. Camilla!

247
00:16:23,232 --> 00:16:25,818
I think this is the night they met.

248
00:16:25,902 --> 00:16:27,778
The night of the Yew Tree Ball.

249
00:16:27,862 --> 00:16:30,573
In no time flat, she'll get herself
established as his official mistress

250
00:16:30,740 --> 00:16:33,075
with her own rooms at the palace,
even her own title.

251
00:16:33,159 --> 00:16:34,994
Madame de Pompadour.

252
00:16:40,208 --> 00:16:42,210
The Queen must have loved her.

253
00:16:42,293 --> 00:16:44,754
No, she did. They got on very well.

254
00:16:44,837 --> 00:16:46,756
The King's wife and the King's girlfriend?

255
00:16:46,881 --> 00:16:49,008
France. It's a different planet.

256
00:16:52,678 --> 00:16:54,096
(TICKING)

257
00:16:55,139 --> 00:16:58,518
How long have you been standing there?
Show yourself!

258
00:17:02,813 --> 00:17:04,815
Hello, Reinette, hasn't time flown!

259
00:17:04,941 --> 00:17:06,901
Fireplace man!

260
00:17:12,448 --> 00:17:14,116
(CREAKING)

261
00:17:14,200 --> 00:17:17,703
-What's it doing?
-Switching back on. Melting the ice.

262
00:17:17,787 --> 00:17:20,873
-And then what?
-Then it kills everyone in the room.

263
00:17:20,957 --> 00:17:24,919
Focuses the mind, doesn't it?
Who are you? Identify yourself.

264
00:17:25,962 --> 00:17:27,630
Order it to answer me.

265
00:17:27,797 --> 00:17:29,215
Why should it listen to me?

266
00:17:29,298 --> 00:17:32,093
I don't know,
but it did when you were a child.

267
00:17:32,176 --> 00:17:34,679
Let's see if you've still got it.

268
00:17:35,012 --> 00:17:36,889
Answer his question.

269
00:17:37,932 --> 00:17:40,935
Answer any and all questions put to you.

270
00:17:44,855 --> 00:17:46,357
I am Repair Droid 7.

271
00:17:46,482 --> 00:17:48,568
And what happened to the ship, then?

272
00:17:48,651 --> 00:17:50,903
There was a lot of damage.

273
00:17:50,987 --> 00:17:53,573
Ion storm. 82% systems failure.

274
00:17:53,656 --> 00:17:56,951
That ship hasn't moved in over a year.
What's taken you so long?

275
00:17:57,034 --> 00:17:59,245
We did not have the parts.

276
00:18:00,621 --> 00:18:03,249
Always comes down to that, doesn't it?
The parts.

277
00:18:03,332 --> 00:18:05,209
What's happened to the crew?
Where are they?

278
00:18:05,293 --> 00:18:07,044
We did not have the parts.

279
00:18:07,128 --> 00:18:10,131
There should've been over 50 people
on your ship. Where did they go?

280
00:18:10,214 --> 00:18:11,757
We did not have the parts.

281
00:18:11,841 --> 00:18:14,844
Fifty people don't just disappear, where...

282
00:18:16,095 --> 00:18:17,221
Oh.

283
00:18:19,056 --> 00:18:22,351
You didn't have the parts
so you used the crew.

284
00:18:23,185 --> 00:18:24,520
The crew?

285
00:18:26,397 --> 00:18:29,066
We found a camera with an eye in it.

286
00:18:29,483 --> 00:18:33,446
And there was a heart
wired into machinery.

287
00:18:34,739 --> 00:18:37,491
It's just doing what it was programmed to.

288
00:18:37,575 --> 00:18:41,537
Repairing the ship any way it can
with whatever it can find.

289
00:18:42,121 --> 00:18:44,415
No one told it
the crew weren't on the menu.

290
00:18:44,498 --> 00:18:47,543
What did you say
the flight deck smelled of?

291
00:18:48,711 --> 00:18:50,421
Someone cooking.

292
00:18:50,504 --> 00:18:52,214
Flesh plus heat.

293
00:18:53,299 --> 00:18:54,634
Barbecue.

294
00:18:56,218 --> 00:18:57,928
But what are you doing here?

295
00:18:58,054 --> 00:19:00,806
You've opened up time windows,
that takes colossal energy.

296
00:19:00,890 --> 00:19:03,726
Why come here?
You could've gone to your repair yard.

297
00:19:03,809 --> 00:19:06,812
Instead you come to 18th-century France?
Why?

298
00:19:06,896 --> 00:19:08,773
One more part is required.

299
00:19:08,856 --> 00:19:10,733
(CREAKING)

300
00:19:13,527 --> 00:19:16,030
Then why haven't you taken it?

301
00:19:16,113 --> 00:19:17,907
She is incomplete.

302
00:19:19,450 --> 00:19:21,243
What? So that's the plan, then?

303
00:19:21,327 --> 00:19:23,829
Just keep opening up
more and more time windows,

304
00:19:23,913 --> 00:19:26,791
scanning her brain,
checking to see if she's done yet?

305
00:19:26,874 --> 00:19:28,376
Why her?

306
00:19:30,419 --> 00:19:34,924
You've got all of history to choose from,
why specifically her?

307
00:19:35,591 --> 00:19:37,677
We are the same.

308
00:19:37,760 --> 00:19:40,262
We're not the same.
We are in no sense the same!

309
00:19:40,388 --> 00:19:42,598
-We are the same.
-Get out of here.

310
00:19:42,682 --> 00:19:45,101
-Get out of here this instant.
-Reinette, no.

311
00:19:45,643 --> 00:19:48,688
It's back on the ship! Rose, take Mickey
and Arthur, get after it, follow it.

312
00:19:48,771 --> 00:19:50,356
Don't approach it, just watch what it does.

313
00:19:50,439 --> 00:19:52,024
-Arthur?
-Good name for a horse.

314
00:19:52,108 --> 00:19:56,320
-No, you're not keeping the horse.
-I let you keep Mickey. Now go, go, go!

315
00:19:59,740 --> 00:20:02,660
You're going to have to trust me.
I need to find out what they're looking for.

316
00:20:02,743 --> 00:20:06,122
There's only one way I can do that.
Won't hurt a bit.

317
00:20:09,166 --> 00:20:10,751
Fireplace man.

318
00:20:11,252 --> 00:20:13,379
You are inside my mind.

319
00:20:13,462 --> 00:20:15,256
Oh, dear, Reinette.

320
00:20:15,840 --> 00:20:17,800
You've had some cowboys in here.

321
00:20:18,467 --> 00:20:21,637
-So, that Doctor, eh?
-What are you talking about?

322
00:20:21,762 --> 00:20:25,433
Well! Madame de Pompadour,
Sarah Jane Smith.

323
00:20:25,599 --> 00:20:28,060
-Cleopatra...
-Cleopatra! He mentioned her once!

324
00:20:28,144 --> 00:20:30,938
-Yeah, but he called her Cleo.
-Mickey!

325
00:20:40,239 --> 00:20:43,492
You are in my memories.
You walk among them.

326
00:20:43,576 --> 00:20:45,327
If there's anything
you don't want me to see,

327
00:20:45,411 --> 00:20:48,622
just imagine a door and close it.
I won't look.

328
00:20:50,332 --> 00:20:53,335
Oh, actually, there's a door just there,
you might want to close...

329
00:20:53,419 --> 00:20:55,421
Oh. Actually, several.

330
00:20:57,465 --> 00:21:00,468
To walk among the memories
of another living soul.

331
00:21:00,551 --> 00:21:03,763
-Do you ever get used to this?
-I don't make a habit of it.

332
00:21:03,846 --> 00:21:06,974
-How can you resist?
-What age are you?

333
00:21:07,057 --> 00:21:10,686
So impertinent a question
so early in the conversation.

334
00:21:11,645 --> 00:21:14,273
-How promising.
-Not my question. Theirs.

335
00:21:14,356 --> 00:21:18,527
You're 23. And for some reason
that means you're not old enough.

336
00:21:18,611 --> 00:21:22,573
Sorry. You might find old memories
reawakening. Side effect.

337
00:21:22,865 --> 00:21:24,742
Oh, such a lonely childhood.

338
00:21:24,825 --> 00:21:26,869
It'll pass. Stay with me.

339
00:21:27,953 --> 00:21:32,625
Oh, Doctor. So lonely. So very, very alone.

340
00:21:32,708 --> 00:21:36,462
What do you mean, alone?
You've never been alone in your life.

341
00:21:36,545 --> 00:21:38,798
When did you start calling me Doctor?

342
00:21:38,881 --> 00:21:41,050
Such a lonely little boy.

343
00:21:41,133 --> 00:21:43,427
Lonely then and lonelier now.

344
00:21:45,221 --> 00:21:48,224
-How can you bear it?
-How did you do that?

345
00:21:49,225 --> 00:21:53,395
A door once opened
may be stepped through in either direction.

346
00:21:54,605 --> 00:21:56,065
Oh, Doctor.

347
00:21:56,899 --> 00:21:58,651
My lonely Doctor.

348
00:22:01,487 --> 00:22:03,072
Dance with me.

349
00:22:03,531 --> 00:22:04,698
I can't.

350
00:22:04,782 --> 00:22:06,659
Dance with me.

351
00:22:06,742 --> 00:22:08,786
This is the night you dance with the King.

352
00:22:08,869 --> 00:22:10,996
Then first I shall make him jealous.

353
00:22:11,080 --> 00:22:13,374
-I can't.
-Doctor.

354
00:22:15,251 --> 00:22:16,710
Doctor who?

355
00:22:19,880 --> 00:22:22,675
It's more than just a secret, isn't it?

356
00:22:23,300 --> 00:22:25,344
What did you see?

357
00:22:26,679 --> 00:22:29,682
That there comes a time, Time Lord,

358
00:22:29,765 --> 00:22:32,935
when every lonely little boy
must learn how to dance.

359
00:22:38,816 --> 00:22:40,401
(TICKING)

360
00:22:45,865 --> 00:22:49,034
What is this? What's going on? Doctor?

361
00:22:49,118 --> 00:22:50,619
MICKEY: Rose?

362
00:22:52,371 --> 00:22:54,206
They're going to chop us up.
Just like the crew!

363
00:22:54,290 --> 00:22:57,251
They're going to chop us up and stick us
all over their stupid spaceship.

364
00:22:57,334 --> 00:22:59,753
And where's the Doctor?
Where's your precious Doctor now?

365
00:22:59,837 --> 00:23:03,716
He's been gone for flipping hours,
that's where he is!

366
00:23:03,799 --> 00:23:05,634
You are compatible.

367
00:23:07,261 --> 00:23:10,556
Well, you might want to think about that.

368
00:23:10,973 --> 00:23:14,518
You really, really might
because me and Mickey,

369
00:23:15,311 --> 00:23:17,688
we didn't come here alone, no, no.

370
00:23:17,813 --> 00:23:21,901
And trust me, you wouldn't want to mess
with our designated driver.

371
00:23:27,114 --> 00:23:30,159
Ever heard of the Daleks? Remember them?

372
00:23:30,659 --> 00:23:32,536
They had a name for our friend.

373
00:23:32,661 --> 00:23:36,165
They had myths about him and a name.
They called him the...

374
00:23:36,290 --> 00:23:40,169
DOCTOR: # I could have danced all night

375
00:23:40,252 --> 00:23:42,671
(STUTTERING) They called him...

376
00:23:42,796 --> 00:23:46,675
# And still have begged for more

377
00:23:47,009 --> 00:23:50,179
# I could have spread my wings
And done a... #

378
00:23:50,304 --> 00:23:52,431
Have you met the French?

379
00:23:52,514 --> 00:23:55,935
My God, they know how to party!

380
00:23:56,018 --> 00:23:59,438
Oh, look at what the cat dragged in.
The Oncoming Storm.

381
00:23:59,563 --> 00:24:01,315
You sound just like your mother.

382
00:24:01,398 --> 00:24:03,359
What have you been doing?
Where have you been?

383
00:24:03,442 --> 00:24:05,527
Well, among other things,

384
00:24:05,611 --> 00:24:09,531
I think I just invented the banana daiquiri
a couple of centuries early.

385
00:24:09,657 --> 00:24:12,534
Do you know,
they'd never even seen a banana before?

386
00:24:12,618 --> 00:24:15,496
Always take a banana to a party, Rose.

387
00:24:15,579 --> 00:24:19,708
Bananas are good. Oh, brilliant.

388
00:24:20,042 --> 00:24:21,961
It's you!

389
00:24:22,044 --> 00:24:24,338
You're my favourite, you are.

390
00:24:24,421 --> 00:24:26,423
You are the best. Do you know why?

391
00:24:26,507 --> 00:24:29,176
'Cause you're so thick.

392
00:24:29,426 --> 00:24:32,471
You're Mr Thick Thick Thicketty Thick-face

393
00:24:32,554 --> 00:24:34,890
from Thick-town, Thickania.

394
00:24:35,891 --> 00:24:38,060
And so is your dad.

395
00:24:38,185 --> 00:24:41,563
Do you know what they were scanning
Reinette's brain for?

396
00:24:41,689 --> 00:24:45,734
Her milometer.
They want to know how old she is.

397
00:24:45,985 --> 00:24:50,239
Know why? 'Cause this ship is 37 years old.

398
00:24:50,364 --> 00:24:54,326
And they think when Reinette is 37,
when she's complete,

399
00:24:54,410 --> 00:24:56,954
then her brain will be compatible.

400
00:24:57,705 --> 00:25:00,249
'Cause that's what you're missing,
isn't it, hmm?

401
00:25:00,374 --> 00:25:02,751
Command circuit, your computer.

402
00:25:02,876 --> 00:25:07,172
Your ship needs a brain.
And for some reason, God knows what,

403
00:25:07,256 --> 00:25:10,718
only the brain
of Madame de Pompadour will do.

404
00:25:11,760 --> 00:25:14,263
The brain is compatible.

405
00:25:14,346 --> 00:25:15,806
Compatible?

406
00:25:16,765 --> 00:25:21,103
If you believe that,
you probably believe this is a glass of wine.

407
00:25:29,194 --> 00:25:32,448
Multi-grade anti-oil. If it moves, it doesn't.

408
00:25:38,454 --> 00:25:42,791
Right, you two, that's enough lying about.
Time we got the rest of the ship turned off.

409
00:25:42,875 --> 00:25:44,960
-Those things safe?
-Yep, safe.

410
00:25:45,085 --> 00:25:46,670
Safe and thick. The way I like them.

411
00:25:46,795 --> 00:25:48,630
Okay, all the time windows
are controlled from here.

412
00:25:48,714 --> 00:25:52,634
Need to close them all down.
Zeus plugs. Where are my Zeus plugs?

413
00:25:52,760 --> 00:25:54,511
Had them a minute ago.
I was using them as castanets.

414
00:25:54,595 --> 00:25:57,139
Why didn't they just open a time window
to when she was 377

415
00:25:57,222 --> 00:25:59,892
Amount of damage to these circuits,
they did well to hit the right century.

416
00:25:59,975 --> 00:26:02,061
Trial and error after that.

417
00:26:02,144 --> 00:26:04,730
The windows aren't closing.
Why won't they close?

418
00:26:04,813 --> 00:26:06,273
(CHIMING)

419
00:26:06,356 --> 00:26:08,609
-What's that?
-I don't know.

420
00:26:08,692 --> 00:26:10,736
-Incoming message?
-MICKEY: From who?

421
00:26:10,819 --> 00:26:12,446
Report from the field.

422
00:26:12,529 --> 00:26:14,406
One of them must still be out there
with Reinette.

423
00:26:14,490 --> 00:26:17,785
That's why I can't close the windows.
There's an override.

424
00:26:17,868 --> 00:26:19,495
(CREAKING)

425
00:26:23,499 --> 00:26:25,459
That was a bit clever.

426
00:26:29,171 --> 00:26:32,674
DOCTOR: Right.
Many things about this are not good.

427
00:26:32,925 --> 00:26:34,426
(CHIMING)

428
00:26:34,510 --> 00:26:37,554
Message from one of your little friends?
Anything interesting?

429
00:26:37,638 --> 00:26:39,848
She is complete. It begins.

430
00:26:44,269 --> 00:26:45,896
What's happening?

431
00:26:45,979 --> 00:26:47,815
One of them must have found
the right time window.

432
00:26:47,898 --> 00:26:49,358
It's time to send in the troops.

433
00:26:49,483 --> 00:26:51,652
And this time
they're bringing back her head.

434
00:26:54,154 --> 00:26:56,198
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

435
00:27:04,706 --> 00:27:06,250
ROSE: Madame de Pompadour.

436
00:27:06,333 --> 00:27:09,044
Please don't scream or anything,
we haven't got a lot of time.

437
00:27:09,169 --> 00:27:11,964
We've come to warn you
that they'll be here in five years.

438
00:27:12,047 --> 00:27:13,465
Five years?

439
00:27:13,549 --> 00:27:16,135
Sometime after your 37th birthday.

440
00:27:16,969 --> 00:27:21,265
I, um, I can't give you an exact date,
it's a bit random.

441
00:27:21,390 --> 00:27:24,184
But they're coming. It's gonna happen.

442
00:27:25,352 --> 00:27:28,313
In a way, for us, it's already happening.

443
00:27:29,731 --> 00:27:33,527
I'm sorry, it's hard to explain.
The Doctor does this better.

444
00:27:33,610 --> 00:27:35,737
Then be exact and I will be attentive.

445
00:27:35,821 --> 00:27:38,740
-There isn't time.
-There are five years.

446
00:27:38,824 --> 00:27:41,076
For you. I haven't got five minutes.

447
00:27:41,160 --> 00:27:43,078
Then also be concise.

448
00:27:45,914 --> 00:27:47,416
Um...

449
00:27:48,458 --> 00:27:51,587
There's a vessel.

450
00:27:51,920 --> 00:27:56,258
A ship. A sort of sky ship. And it's full of...

451
00:27:57,467 --> 00:27:59,511
Well, you.

452
00:27:59,595 --> 00:28:02,973
Different bits of your life
in different rooms. All jumbled up.

453
00:28:03,098 --> 00:28:05,893
I told you it was complicated, sorry.

454
00:28:06,435 --> 00:28:09,605
There is a vessel in your world

455
00:28:09,688 --> 00:28:11,815
where the days of my life
are pressed together

456
00:28:11,940 --> 00:28:13,817
like the chapters of a book

457
00:28:13,901 --> 00:28:17,446
so that he may step from one to the other
without increase of age

458
00:28:17,571 --> 00:28:20,365
while I, weary traveller,

459
00:28:20,449 --> 00:28:22,826
must always take the slower path.

460
00:28:22,910 --> 00:28:24,912
He was right about you.

461
00:28:26,079 --> 00:28:29,374
So in five years these creatures will return.
What can be done?

462
00:28:29,458 --> 00:28:31,126
The Doctor says keep them talking.

463
00:28:31,210 --> 00:28:34,504
They're kind of programmed
to respond to you now.

464
00:28:34,630 --> 00:28:38,258
You won't be able to stop them,
but you might be able to delay them a bit.

465
00:28:38,342 --> 00:28:41,220
-Until?
-Until the Doctor can get there.

466
00:28:41,303 --> 00:28:43,722
-He's coming, then?
-He promises.

467
00:28:44,223 --> 00:28:47,226
But he cannot make his promises
in person?

468
00:28:48,477 --> 00:28:51,980
He'll be there when you need him.
That's the way it's got to be.

469
00:28:52,064 --> 00:28:54,483
It's the way it's always been.

470
00:28:54,900 --> 00:28:57,152
The monsters and the Doctor.

471
00:28:57,778 --> 00:29:00,364
It seems you cannot have one
without the other.

472
00:29:00,447 --> 00:29:02,491
Tell me about it.

473
00:29:04,201 --> 00:29:07,955
The thing is,
you weren't supposed to have either.

474
00:29:08,622 --> 00:29:10,999
Those creatures are messing with history.

475
00:29:11,124 --> 00:29:13,168
None of this was ever
supposed to happen to you.

476
00:29:13,252 --> 00:29:16,171
Supposed to happen?
What does that mean?

477
00:29:17,089 --> 00:29:21,009
It happened, child.
And I would not have it any other way.

478
00:29:21,802 --> 00:29:25,430
One may tolerate a world of demons
for the sake of an angel.

479
00:29:28,809 --> 00:29:31,019
MICKEY: Rose? Rose!

480
00:29:32,854 --> 00:29:34,231
Rose!

481
00:29:34,356 --> 00:29:38,860
The time window where she's 37.
We've found it, right under our noses.

482
00:29:42,322 --> 00:29:45,701
No, you can't go in there.
The Doctor will go mad.

483
00:29:52,874 --> 00:29:54,751
So this is his world.

484
00:29:54,835 --> 00:29:56,586
(WOMAN SCREAMING)

485
00:29:57,254 --> 00:29:59,006
What was that?

486
00:29:59,089 --> 00:30:01,466
The time window.
The Doctor fixed an audio link.

487
00:30:01,550 --> 00:30:04,845
Those screams. Is that my future?

488
00:30:05,512 --> 00:30:07,306
Yeah, I'm sorry.

489
00:30:07,389 --> 00:30:09,808
Then I must take the slower path.

490
00:30:09,891 --> 00:30:12,769
REINETTE: Are you there? Can you hear me?

491
00:30:12,853 --> 00:30:16,898
I need you now. You promised. The clock
on the mantel is broken. It is time!

492
00:30:16,982 --> 00:30:18,233
That's my voice.

493
00:30:18,358 --> 00:30:20,736
Rose, come on, we've got to go.
There's a problem.

494
00:30:20,819 --> 00:30:22,529
Give me a moment.

495
00:30:29,828 --> 00:30:31,538
-You okay?
-No.

496
00:30:32,247 --> 00:30:34,041
I'm very afraid.

497
00:30:34,124 --> 00:30:37,169
But you and I both know, don't we, Rose?

498
00:30:37,252 --> 00:30:39,755
The Doctor is worth the monsters.

499
00:30:47,137 --> 00:30:49,264
REINETTE: Doctor! Doctor!

500
00:30:50,223 --> 00:30:51,558
(SCREAMING)

501
00:30:55,062 --> 00:30:57,230
(CREAKING)

502
00:31:06,782 --> 00:31:08,075
Doctor!

503
00:31:08,450 --> 00:31:11,328
We must go! No one is coming to help us.

504
00:31:20,379 --> 00:31:22,798
You are complete. You will come.

505
00:31:23,632 --> 00:31:25,675
(SCREAMING)

506
00:31:32,307 --> 00:31:33,725
You found it, then?

507
00:31:33,809 --> 00:31:36,269
They knew I was coming,
they've blocked it off.

508
00:31:36,353 --> 00:31:39,314
-Where are we going?
-The teleport has limited range.

509
00:31:39,398 --> 00:31:42,025
We must have proximity to the time portal.

510
00:31:42,150 --> 00:31:45,112
Your words mean nothing. You are nothing.

511
00:31:47,656 --> 00:31:50,283
-How come they got in there?
-They teleported.

512
00:31:50,367 --> 00:31:52,244
As long as the ship
and the ballroom are linked,

513
00:31:52,327 --> 00:31:53,870
their short-range teleports will do the trick.

514
00:31:53,954 --> 00:31:56,998
-We'll go in the Tardis.
-We can't. We're part of events now.

515
00:31:57,082 --> 00:31:58,500
Can't we just smash through?

516
00:31:58,583 --> 00:32:00,627
Hyperplex this side, plate glass the other.
We'd need a truck.

517
00:32:00,710 --> 00:32:02,629
-We don't have a truck.
-I know!

518
00:32:02,712 --> 00:32:04,131
We've got to try something!

519
00:32:04,214 --> 00:32:05,841
No. Smash the glass,
smash the time windows.

520
00:32:05,924 --> 00:32:07,634
There'd be no way back.

521
00:32:07,717 --> 00:32:11,513
Could everyone just calm down!

522
00:32:12,180 --> 00:32:13,932
Please!

523
00:32:14,057 --> 00:32:17,185
Such a commotion. Such distressing noise.

524
00:32:17,310 --> 00:32:21,022
Kindly remember that this is Versailles.

525
00:32:21,231 --> 00:32:24,651
This is the Royal Court and we are French.

526
00:32:30,073 --> 00:32:32,033
I have made a decision.

527
00:32:32,659 --> 00:32:34,953
And my decision is no.

528
00:32:35,036 --> 00:32:37,873
I shall not be going with you today.

529
00:32:37,956 --> 00:32:41,960
I have seen your world and
I have no desire to set foot there again.

530
00:32:43,086 --> 00:32:45,380
We do not require your feet.

531
00:32:47,507 --> 00:32:49,134
(ALL GASPING)

532
00:32:56,099 --> 00:33:00,228
You think I fear you,
but I do not fear you even now.

533
00:33:01,396 --> 00:33:05,734
You are merely
the nightmare of my childhood,

534
00:33:05,817 --> 00:33:07,986
the monster from under my bed.

535
00:33:08,069 --> 00:33:10,447
And if my nightmare
can return to plague me,

536
00:33:10,530 --> 00:33:13,241
then rest assured, so will yours.

537
00:33:13,366 --> 00:33:15,035
(HORSE WHINNYING)

538
00:33:15,118 --> 00:33:16,912
(HORSE GALLOPING)

539
00:33:26,838 --> 00:33:28,256
(SCREAMING)

540
00:33:47,442 --> 00:33:50,737
Madame de Pompadour.
You look younger every day.

541
00:33:51,613 --> 00:33:53,782
What the hell is going on?

542
00:33:53,907 --> 00:33:57,577
Oh. This is my lover, the King of France.

543
00:33:58,119 --> 00:34:00,914
Yeah? Well, I'm the Lord of Time.

544
00:34:03,833 --> 00:34:05,919
And I'm here to fix the clock.

545
00:34:06,002 --> 00:34:07,379
(ALL GASPING)

546
00:34:08,547 --> 00:34:10,257
Forget it. It's over.

547
00:34:11,800 --> 00:34:13,426
For you and for me.

548
00:34:15,053 --> 00:34:17,556
Talk about seven years' bad luck.

549
00:34:18,848 --> 00:34:20,475
Try 3,000.

550
00:34:20,559 --> 00:34:21,935
(CREAKING)

551
00:34:27,023 --> 00:34:28,984
MICKEY: What happened?

552
00:34:29,109 --> 00:34:32,904
Where did the time window go?
How's he gonna get back?

553
00:34:50,672 --> 00:34:53,216
The link with the ship is broken.
No way back.

554
00:34:55,010 --> 00:34:57,137
You don't have the parts.

555
00:34:58,722 --> 00:35:02,350
How many ticks left
in that clockwork heart, huh?

556
00:35:02,475 --> 00:35:04,519
A day? An hour?

557
00:35:06,021 --> 00:35:09,024
It's over. Accept that.

558
00:35:10,650 --> 00:35:12,652
I'm not winding you up.

559
00:35:28,043 --> 00:35:29,669
Are you all right?

560
00:35:31,755 --> 00:35:33,882
What's happened to them?

561
00:35:34,966 --> 00:35:36,718
They've stopped.

562
00:35:38,178 --> 00:35:40,263
They have no purpose now.

563
00:35:51,358 --> 00:35:54,027
We can't fly the Tardis without him.

564
00:35:54,402 --> 00:35:55,945
How's he gonna get back?

565
00:36:13,171 --> 00:36:15,757
You know all their names, don't you?

566
00:36:16,216 --> 00:36:18,551
I saw that in your mind.

567
00:36:18,635 --> 00:36:20,553
The name of every star.

568
00:36:20,637 --> 00:36:22,263
What's in a name?

569
00:36:22,389 --> 00:36:25,266
Names are just titles.
Titles don't tell you anything.

570
00:36:25,350 --> 00:36:27,268
Like "the Doctor"?

571
00:36:27,435 --> 00:36:29,604
Like "Madame de Pompadour”.

572
00:36:32,399 --> 00:36:35,735
I have often wished to see those stars
a little closer.

573
00:36:35,819 --> 00:36:37,821
Just as you have, I think.

574
00:36:37,946 --> 00:36:39,739
From time to time.

575
00:36:40,490 --> 00:36:43,118
In saving me, you trapped yourself.

576
00:36:43,410 --> 00:36:45,453
Did you know that would happen?

577
00:36:45,537 --> 00:36:47,622
Hmm, pretty much.

578
00:36:47,789 --> 00:36:49,791
Yet still you came.

579
00:36:49,874 --> 00:36:53,545
Yeah, I did, didn't I?
Catch me doing that again.

580
00:36:55,588 --> 00:36:58,800
There were many doors
between my world and yours.

581
00:36:58,883 --> 00:37:01,094
Can you not use one of the others?

582
00:37:01,177 --> 00:37:02,554
When the mirror broke,

583
00:37:02,637 --> 00:37:04,764
the shock would've severed
all the links with the ship.

584
00:37:04,848 --> 00:37:09,394
There'll be a few more broken mirrors
and torn tapestries around here I'm afraid,

585
00:37:09,477 --> 00:37:11,646
wherever there was a time window.

586
00:37:11,730 --> 00:37:14,649
(STAMMERING) I'll pay for any damage.

587
00:37:16,609 --> 00:37:18,820
That's a thought, I'm gonna need money.

588
00:37:18,903 --> 00:37:20,989
I've always been a bit vague about money.

589
00:37:22,031 --> 00:37:24,367
Where do you get money?

590
00:37:24,451 --> 00:37:26,119
So here you are.

591
00:37:27,162 --> 00:37:29,164
My lonely angel.

592
00:37:29,789 --> 00:37:32,167
Stuck on the slow path with me.

593
00:37:32,292 --> 00:37:34,169
Yep. The slow path.

594
00:37:35,712 --> 00:37:37,297
Here's to the slow path.

595
00:37:37,380 --> 00:37:39,674
(REINETTE LAUGHS)

596
00:37:42,969 --> 00:37:47,182
It's a pity.
I think I would have enjoyed the slow path.

597
00:37:48,016 --> 00:37:50,268
Well, I'm not going anywhere.

598
00:37:51,227 --> 00:37:52,854
Oh, aren't you?

599
00:37:54,731 --> 00:37:56,274
Take my hand.

600
00:38:18,213 --> 00:38:20,799
It's not a copy. It's the original.

601
00:38:21,800 --> 00:38:25,136
I had it moved here
and was exact in every detail.

602
00:38:26,721 --> 00:38:28,306
The fireplace.

603
00:38:31,309 --> 00:38:33,770
The fireplace from your bedroom.

604
00:38:36,272 --> 00:38:39,234
-When did you do this?
-Many years ago.

605
00:38:40,443 --> 00:38:44,739
In the hope that a door once opened
may someday open again.

606
00:38:46,950 --> 00:38:49,994
One never quite knows
when one needs one's doctor.

607
00:38:52,539 --> 00:38:55,500
It appears undamaged.
Do you think it will still work?

608
00:38:55,583 --> 00:38:57,669
You broke the bond with the ship
when you moved it.

609
00:38:57,752 --> 00:38:59,921
Which means it was off-line
when the mirror broke.

610
00:39:00,004 --> 00:39:01,923
That's what saved it.

611
00:39:03,216 --> 00:39:04,425
But...

612
00:39:05,885 --> 00:39:10,014
the link is basically physical
and it's still physically here,

613
00:39:12,225 --> 00:39:15,103
which might just mean, if I'm lucky,

614
00:39:15,186 --> 00:39:17,981
if I'm very, very, very, very, very lucky...

615
00:39:20,149 --> 00:39:21,651
-Aha!
-What?

616
00:39:21,776 --> 00:39:23,695
Loose connection!

617
00:39:23,778 --> 00:39:25,655
Need to get a man in!

618
00:39:27,866 --> 00:39:30,535
-Wish me luck.
-No.

619
00:39:35,957 --> 00:39:37,792
Madame de Pompadour!

620
00:39:39,627 --> 00:39:41,212
Still wanna see those stars?

621
00:39:41,296 --> 00:39:44,132
-More than anything.
-Give me two minutes. Pack a bag.

622
00:39:44,215 --> 00:39:45,550
Am I going somewhere?

623
00:39:45,633 --> 00:39:48,469
Go to the window. Pick a star. Any star.

624
00:40:01,691 --> 00:40:03,902
-How long did you wait?
-Five and half hours.

625
00:40:03,985 --> 00:40:06,112
Great! Always wait five and half hours.

626
00:40:06,195 --> 00:40:07,322
Where've you been?

627
00:40:07,405 --> 00:40:10,450
Explain later. Into the Tardis.
With you in a sec!

628
00:40:10,533 --> 00:40:11,910
DOCTOR: Reinette.

629
00:40:13,661 --> 00:40:15,538
Are you there, Reinette?

630
00:40:27,508 --> 00:40:28,843
Reinette?

631
00:40:30,678 --> 00:40:32,347
Oh, hello.

632
00:40:33,640 --> 00:40:35,516
You just missed her.

633
00:40:36,517 --> 00:40:39,395
-She'll be in Paris by 6:00.
-Oh.

634
00:40:42,690 --> 00:40:44,067
Good Lord!

635
00:40:45,276 --> 00:40:46,861
She was right.

636
00:40:47,862 --> 00:40:50,657
She said you never looked a day older.

637
00:40:51,282 --> 00:40:55,745
So many years since I saw you last,
but not a day of it on your face.

638
00:41:06,881 --> 00:41:09,133
She spoke of you many times.

639
00:41:10,969 --> 00:41:13,388
Often wished you'd visit again.

640
00:41:14,138 --> 00:41:16,099
You know how women are.

641
00:41:19,686 --> 00:41:22,021
(HORSES WHINNYING)

642
00:41:23,231 --> 00:41:25,066
(CARRIAGE DEPARTING)

643
00:41:29,153 --> 00:41:30,947
And there she goes.

644
00:41:31,656 --> 00:41:34,409
Leaving Versailles for the last time.

645
00:41:36,244 --> 00:41:38,162
Only 43 when she died.

646
00:41:39,914 --> 00:41:41,332
Too young.

647
00:41:42,667 --> 00:41:44,085
Too young.

648
00:41:45,920 --> 00:41:48,214
Illness took her in the end.

649
00:41:49,382 --> 00:41:51,759
She always did work too hard.

650
00:41:58,307 --> 00:42:00,059
What does she say?

651
00:42:10,695 --> 00:42:12,113
Of course.

652
00:42:13,489 --> 00:42:14,949
Quite right.

653
00:42:34,510 --> 00:42:36,095
ROSE: Why her?

654
00:42:37,346 --> 00:42:39,348
Why did they think
they could repair the ship

655
00:42:39,432 --> 00:42:41,726
with the head of Madame de Pompadour?

656
00:42:41,809 --> 00:42:43,936
We'll probably never know.

657
00:42:44,020 --> 00:42:46,355
There's massive damage
in the computer memory decks.

658
00:42:46,439 --> 00:42:48,691
Probably got confused.

659
00:42:48,775 --> 00:42:51,027
The Tardis can close down
the time windows

660
00:42:51,152 --> 00:42:53,404
now the droids have gone.

661
00:42:53,488 --> 00:42:56,449
Should stop it causing any more trouble.

662
00:42:59,994 --> 00:43:01,496
You all right?

663
00:43:02,705 --> 00:43:04,624
I'm always all right.

664
00:43:10,671 --> 00:43:15,009
Come on, Rose, it's time you showed me
round the rest of this place.

665
00:43:34,695 --> 00:43:37,824
REINETTE: "My dear Doctor,

666
00:43:37,907 --> 00:43:42,620
“the path has never seemed more slow
and yet I fear I am nearing its end.

667
00:43:43,579 --> 00:43:47,250
"Reason tells me that you and I
are unlikely to meet again,

668
00:43:47,375 --> 00:43:50,336
"but I think I shall not listen to reason.

669
00:43:50,503 --> 00:43:55,424
"I have seen the world inside your head
and know that all things are possible.

670
00:43:56,050 --> 00:43:58,302
"Hurry, though, my love.

671
00:43:58,386 --> 00:44:01,556
"My days grow shorter now
and I am so very weak.

672
00:44:02,473 --> 00:44:04,767
"Godspeed, my lonely angel.”

673
00:44:43,014 --> 00:44:45,141
(WHOOSHING)

674
00:45:13,586 --> 00:45:14,795
DOCTOR: So this is London.

675
00:45:14,879 --> 00:45:16,714
An alternative to our world
where everything's the same

676
00:45:16,797 --> 00:45:18,299
but a little bit different.

677
00:45:18,382 --> 00:45:20,718
We're in some sort of no place.

678
00:45:20,801 --> 00:45:23,596
All those people
disappearing off the streets,

679
00:45:23,679 --> 00:45:25,431
it's been going on for months.

680
00:45:26,849 --> 00:45:29,560
-What are they all doing?
-DOCTOR: It's the earpieces.

681
00:45:30,603 --> 00:45:33,439
MAN: The prototype
has passed every test, sir.

682
00:45:33,522 --> 00:45:35,316
It's working.

683
00:45:35,399 --> 00:45:37,318
I've seen them before.

684
00:45:37,401 --> 00:45:39,111
ROSE: What are they?

685
00:45:39,195 --> 00:45:43,574
Skin of metal and
a body that will never age.

686
00:45:43,658 --> 00:45:44,825
Cybers.

